What is the structure of your dataset?¶

In the dataset, there are 16 columns in total, including gender, user type, date of birth, names of bike stations, IDs of each bike, starting station, last station, latitude and longitude of stations, journey time, start time and end time. Most of the variables are numeric in nature, there are also date and time and categorical variables. user type:Customer,subscriber member gender:male,female

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I'm most interested in figuring out which properties are best in relation to the date, time, user type, and travel time of the users in the dataset.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

My expectation is that the most used days are weekdays, and the average age of those who use weekends may increase. Because the high average age group is likely to use bicycles to have a pleasant time on the weekend.

Univariate Exploration¶

I'll start by looking at the distribution of the main variable of interest:user type.

In [28]:
def plot_pie_chart (data_source, column, title):
    sorted_counts = bike['user_type'].value_counts()
    plt.pie(sorted_counts, labels = sorted_counts.index, startangle = 90,explode=[0.2,0],autopct='%1.1f%%')
    plt.title("User Type Rates")
plot_pie_chart(bike, "user_type", "User Type Rates")

The most user type was subscribers with ½ 89.2.

In [29]:
def bagel_pie_chart (data_source, column, title):
    gender_counts = bike['member_gender'].value_counts()
    plt.pie(gender_counts, labels = gender_counts.index, startangle = 90,autopct='%1.1f%%',wedgeprops = {'width' : 0.4})
    plt.title("Gender Rates")

bagel_pie_chart(bike, "member_gender", "Gender Rates")

According to gender, the highest number of users was male with ½ 74.6.

In [30]:
def bar_chart(data_source, column, title):
    bike['start_hour']=pd.to_datetime(bike['start_time']).dt.hour
    order = np.arange(0,24)
    sb.countplot(x=bike["start_hour"],order=order)
    plt.title("total number of rides by Start hour")
bar_chart(bike,"start_hour","total number of rides by Start hour")
In [31]:
def bar_chart(data_source, column, title):
    bike['end_hour']=pd.to_datetime(bike['end_time']).dt.hour
    order = np.arange(0,24)
    sb.countplot(x=bike["end_hour"],order=order)
    plt.title("total number of rides by End hour")
bar_chart(bike,"end_hour","total number of rides by end hour")

When we look at the start and end times, the most bicycle traffic occurred between business hours (07-18).

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

Users are mostly subscribers, and mostly men use bicycles. Bicycles are mostly used between business hours (7-18). It is used more on weekdays than on weekends, which may be because most people prefer cycling to and from work. they prefer bicycles for a short time, mostly those in their 30s.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

I added age, hour and day columns from the data because I produced more meaningful results on the data. Especially after a certain age, I had the opportunity to discover how people use their bicycles and the times they use bicycles the most.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

We see that young people between 22-03 hours use it more and the population under 50 comes with longer travel times. We can see that bicycles are used more between 08-17 hours, and people use bicycles for longer journeys in the morning and evening hours.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

Although there is the most bicycle use on Thursday, when we look at the average travel time, it is the day with the least. Thursday can be a busy day for business life. We see that average travel time increases significantly on weekends. I thought this was because people used bikes for weekend rides and recreation.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

It shows that bike company users do short-term bike rides every day of the week and have users on the younger age scale and it is possible to see that subscribers behave more consistently and users of all ages, but it is a bit difficult to see them in customers

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

It may be that there is a negative correlation between age and journey time, both between users and customers.

Conclusions¶

The results of my analysis focused on discovering and visualizing the usage habits of age-related subscribers and consumers on the days of the week and at certain times of the day.that the company is predominantly male users, mostly 30s. that it is used more frequently but in short time intervals on weekdays, longer and less on weekends. There was a negative relationship between age and travel time.
